4264_Final_Hackathon : Auto Insurance Claim¶

Business Case¶

As we relate to Insurance business, these days lot of insurance companies are dealing with the problem of fraudulent claims.

Fraud affects the lives of innocent people as well as the insurance industry as industry faces the losses and as a result of which peoples need to suffer by increased premiums. Thus we can say, it may be of interest for the health of the Insurance Industry and Society.

Insurance fraud claim refers to any claim which intent to obtain an improper payment from an insurer.

Auto insurance fraud includes: misrepresenting facts on an insurance application; submitting claims for injuries or damage that never occurred; staging accidents; and also false reports of stolen vehicles.

According to the FBI (Federal Bureau of Investigation), non-health insurance fraud costs an estimated 40 billion doller per year, which means Insurance Fraud cost the average U.S. family between 400 doller and 700 doller per year in the form of increased premiums. (source: https://www.fbi.gov/stats-services/publications/insurance-fraud)

So to overcome this, the manual procedure of analyzing vehicle insurance claims necessitates the hiring of highly skilled fraud reviewers, which makes detecting fraud time-consuming, expensive, and unscalable as the number of claims increases.

Machine Learning can be used, among other tools, to uncover fraud before a payment. These newer strategies are employed when claims are initially filed. Suspicious claims are flagged for further review, while those with no apparent questionable elements are processed normally.

The framework of prediction of fraud and pattern extraction wil be useful for the insurance companies, regulatory body, intelligence department etc.

Problem Statement¶

The goal of this hackathon project is to build a generalized model that can detect whether the claim of auto insurance is fraudulent or not(legit). The challenge behind fraud detection in machine learning is that frauds are far less common as compared to legit insurance claims. This type of problems is known as imbalanced class classification. So by building a model that can classify auto insurance fraud, I am able to cut losses for the insurance company. Fewer losses equates to more earning to the business of Insurance company..

About The Dataset¶

There are four types of dataset is provided for this problem statement which includes:

  1. Demographics Data : These files consist of the demographic data of each customer, like CustomerID, Country,InsuredAge, InsuredGender, InsuredEducationLevel,etc .
  2. Policy Information : These files consist of the customer auto insurance policy information, connected to the claim with the insurance company, like, CustomerID, InsurancePolicyNumber, DateOfPolicyCoverage, InsurancePolicyState, UmbrellaLimit, etc.
  3. Data of Claim : These files consist of the details about the insurance claim, that the customer applied for, like DateOfIncident, TypeOfIncident, AmountOfInjuryclaim, AmountOfPropertyClaim, etc.
  4. Data of Vehicle : These files consist of the details about the Vehicle, connected to the policy.
  5. Fraud Data : This contains the Fraud information details, like CustomerID, ReportedFraud.

Note: We need to merge all the dataset to make a final dataset on the common feature among all ,ie., CustomerID. But before that, we can observe that Vehicle_csv is not having same number of rows like other datasets. So we need to try to use some method to make its rows equal to other dataset, so only we can perform merge operation here. I have used here Pivot table() which helped me in achieving the same number of rows as it created new features like VehicleID, VehicleMake, VehicleModel and VehicleYOM.

Detection : IQR (Inter Quartile Range)¶

Data points that lie 1.5 times of IQR above Q3 and below Q1 are outliers

IQR = Quartile3 – Quartile1

Quartile1 =25 percentile of data
Quartile3 =75 percentile of data

upper = Q3 +1.5*IQR
lower = Q1 – 1.5*IQR
In [113]:
## Checking for outliers in the numerical features.

for col in num_df:

    q1=np.percentile(num_df[col],25) 
    q3=np.percentile(num_df[col],75)

    IQR=q3-q1
    
    print('Outliers for :',col,'\n')
    #print(q1,q3,IQR)

#detecting upper bounds
    upper=q3+1.5*IQR
    #print('Upper',upper)

    up=num_df[col]>=upper
    #print(np.where(up))


#detectiong lower bounds
    lower=q1-1.5*IQR
    #print('lower',lower)

    lw=num_df[col]<=lower
    #print(np.where(lw),'\n')
    
    outliers=[]
    for i in num_df[col]:
        if(i<lower or i>upper):
            outliers.append(i)
    print("Outliers are:",outliers)
    print("\n")

Outlier_Treatment : Quantile based flooring and capping¶

The data points that are lesser than the 10th percentile are replaced with the 10th percentile value and 
the data points that are greater than the 90th percentile are replaced with 90th percentile value.
In [114]:
## Outlier treatment


for col in num_df:
    tenth_percentile=np.percentile(num_df[col],10)
    ninetieth_percentile=np.percentile(num_df[col],90)
    print(tenth_percentile,ninetieth_percentile)
    num_df[col]=np.where(num_df[col]<tenth_percentile,tenth_percentile,num_df[col]) 
    num_df[col]=np.where(num_df[col]>ninetieth_percentile,ninetieth_percentile,num_df[col])

In [115]:
for col in num_df:

    q1=np.percentile(num_df[col],25) 
    q3=np.percentile(num_df[col],75)

    IQR=q3-q1
    
    print('Outliers for :',col,'\n')
    #print(q1,q3,IQR)

#detecting upper bounds
    upper=q3+1.5*IQR
    #print('Upper',upper)

    up=num_df[col]>=upper
    #print(np.where(up))


#detectiong lower bounds
    lower=q1-1.5*IQR
    #print('lower',lower)

    lw=num_df[col]<=lower
    #print(np.where(lw),'\n')
    
    outliers=[]
    for i in num_df[col]:
        if(i<lower or i>upper):
            outliers.append(i)
    print("Outliers are:",outliers)
    print("\n")

            outliers.append(i)
    print("Outliers are:",outliers)
    print("\n")
